Tell your slicer to add a pause at that layer, and switch filament to a contrasting color while paused. My printer will keep the motors locked in place for about five minutes while paused. Beyond that time, the motors will be off when I go to switch filament, which inevitably moves the X (and sometimes Y) axis out of position a little bit. In this case, I send a command (G28 XY) to have the printer home the X and Y axes before resuming the print.

description.text:
Use the Gravity Gauge sign to display the current day's gravity forecast. When kept up-to-date, your sign will tell people when they can bounce around in low gravity, or if they should stay home when gravity is unbearable. The original sign was designed by Miguel Marquez, who allowed me to post the 3D version here.

Miguel's version has LED lights, this one uses a two-piece sliding indicator. If the arrow is not snug enough to stay put on the sign, attach some flat fridge magnets to the back of the sign and stick it to a metal surface. The sign is thin enough to bend and hold the arrow, keeping it from falling.

Notes:

Use your slicer to determine at what layer the sign's background stops printing and the text begins. Tell your slicer to add a pause at that layer, and switch filament to a contrasting color while paused. My printer will keep the motors locked in place for about five minutes while paused. Beyond that time, the motors will be off when I go to switch filament, which inevitably moves the X (and sometimes Y) axis out of position a little bit. In this case, I send a command (G28 XY) to have the printer home the X and Y axes before resuming the print.

Snap arrow to sign

The two-piece indicator arrow is a bit difficult to snap together. The task can be made easier by using a hobby knife to take the sharp corners off the bottom of rectangular retainer piece. I also found a bit of oil helped reduce friction in this area.

description.text:
I was using the RC4G for drifting. But I found the trigger inconvenient for braking - too much travel, and impossible to find the exact position for the right amount of throttle afterwards. So, I decided to use the third channel for e-brake (or fourth as Radiolink calls it, since it names #3 for gyro sensitivity).
Programming it was very easy, and the button was correctly set up for use as an e-brake: only active while pressed (in other radios the button works as an on/off switch). The problem was, of course, the positioning of the button: to press it while playing, you need a thumb with at least three joints!
So I designed this little 'button presser'. It slips around the gyro sensitivity adjustment knob which holds it tight, and with the index finger you press it and the pressing goes to the button.

It works as a charm!

Two variations, with different size above the button. I think the 2mm one is perfect.

Have fun!

EDIT: The TrackStar D-Spec TS4G seems to be exactly the same box, so it should work with it also.

title: Cisco Room Kit and Room Kit Plus Stand

description.text:
Cisco Room Kit device is provided with wall and VESA mount options. Room Kit Plus device with wall mount only. No legs for desk or top of display placement are available. I tried to fill the gap and created the legs for both types of devices. Room Kit's camera is tilted and the original wall mount bar has two sides - one for above display and the other for below display placement. The below display side is tilted by 15 degrees. So I have created two versions of legs - "above" which is straight and "below" tilted by 15 degrees. Room Kit Plus's camera looks straight and can be adjusted by up to 15 degrees. For below display placement "15deg" stand is available.

If you want to create your own legs, the "click" mechanisms are included in separate files so you can place them on top of your creation. Remember the legs should be at least 50mm high for proper cable management - all cable connectors point straight downward from the Room Kits. Do not forget the Room Kit weighs 3.2 kg and Room Kit Plus 4.8 kg and the legs should be stiff in front-back direction to avoid vibrations.

The recommended print position is on side, supports required.

title: Lasercut-Art inspired by Escher and the Autumn

description.text:
Hi there!
This is a laser cut piece inspired by the work of M.C. Escher. The work is inspired by mathematical patterns and the autumn season in which I designed this piece.
The idea is that one shape (in this case a leaf) is repeated throughout the work using translations and rotations. The shape is specific and are often referred to their 'grundtype' (see illustration). The grundtype used in this work is C3C3C3C3. 
I love seeing my work somewhere else, if you do decide to use my design, please be so kind to mention me as the original designer, thank you.

I glued three different collored wallpapers to 3mm thick MDF, laser cut the files (black is engraving, red is cutting). I used one of the borders from the plates and glued it to a same size/thickness plate. I started assembling the leafs by glueing them on the plate using wood glue.

description.text:
When you purchase an UP! or an Afinia H480, the bed includes spring clips used to hold perf-boards in place. These boards warp and it's very hard to get a good flat print. The solution: Afinia sells 3mm borosilicate glass plates that fit perfectly on the print bed, but first you have to remove the spring clips. When you buy sheets of glass from Afinia they include clips that hold the glass at the back of the bed, and metal clips to hold the glass in place in front.

SAVE THOSE SCREWS!

I found for a long time that I sometimes forget to clip the glass at the front and I have broken more than one sheet of glass this way, when the glass slides off the front down to my concrete floor. I have fixed that in two ways: I installed a foam floor under my printers, and I invented this clip to stop the glass from sliding forward.

This project includes two rear clips to replace the AFINIA clips, and because Afinia clips can slip, and every time you put the glass in place you have to ensure they are firmly in place, I made these so they screw into the plate from below using the same screws that used to hold those spring clips.

The front clip also screws in place and prevents the glass from accidentally falling off.

I still recommend using the metal clips at the front-sides for a perfect print.

THIS IS A HUGE IMPROVEMENT OVER THE ORIGINAL PRINTED REAR CLIPS!

title: Microquad frame 8520 motor Eachine QX95 frame replacement

description.text:
This frame is to replace the original Eachine QX95 frame, this frame has proven to be more durable and is very similar in weight. The camera holder is angle-adjustable and tends to fold back to protect the cloverleaf in a crash. All parts for the QX95 transfer over (flight board, motors, camera, LED assembly), and after they are installed the frame can be replaced without any unsoldering/resoldering (I can swap a frame in about 1-2 minutes). I made some flexible (TPU) motor guards for the front arms. Everything holds together with small elastics, the LED strip friction-fits in the frame. for cameras larger than that of the original QX95, the camera holder may need to be modified a little to make space. I have used this frame a lot and it has proven to work great. We race in a shop full of concrete and steel so these need to be durable. The stem through the coverleaf and fact the antenna folds back has worked great for keeping the antenna safe.

I would expect most similar quad could use this frame (eg. qx90..etc)

There is also a cover to streamline assembly, covering up the flight board, but i dont use it anymore.
You will probably need to scale everything x10 to get it to the correct size.

Some of the parts shown were printed with a wore-out nozzle, so they dont look great.

P.S. those tri blade props do not work well, i was just experimenting with them. They are very quiet, but have much less thrust.

description.text:
Hello!
This is my G3DK project. The set contains the following items:

The complete extruder (Chimera Chinese version) including belt holder, fan holder, LED holder and cable holder.
The stepper motor holders for the Z-axis
Stepper motor holder for the X-axis

This construction is based on the linear guides MGN12, the upper stepper motor brackets are pushed onto the guides and hold by themselves. If this is not the case, there is a hole for screwing in the holders. The motor couplings MUST be free of play!

The linear guides are mounted laterally and the distance to the frame is very small to minimize vibrations and levers. This makes the print much cleaner.

The X-axis holders are designed for 2020 extrusion.

I would print the stepper motor holders and belt holders made of PETG because this material does not break and is very tough. During my first attempts with ABS I broke the belt holder.
The belt wedges hold the belt perfectly and do not require any screws.
There are various Chinese extruder designs. The top three holes may need to be adjusted.

The holder for the radial fans is also included. I didn't upload a nozzle because I'm still dissatisfied with it. I will upload them later.

I recommend printing the belt holders with at least 50%. Also the bracket for the cable holder. The rest can be printed with 30%.

As a fan I use an E3D-Titan Aero fan. This is switched on and off automatically at 70°C.
With this conversion I can print PLA up to 180mm/s without any problems.

You can find the belt tensioner for the X-axis in my other projects.

I took the chocks from the belt holder from another project, this is Remix. Unfortunately I can't find the link to it anymore.

title: RocketEd Rocket adapted to C6-5
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
first of all thx to rockeded for the nice design. as it was stated that this one is not designed for the c-series motors, i decided to adapt it a bit.

for this i had to make the prop-base a bit longer. i also introduced a little ring to strengthen the top part of the prop base, as i was not sure, if this part would survive the blast for the parachute. i decided to do this quite late in the process, which is why i didn't design the ring into the prop-base right away. this one slides on and needs a few drops of acetone to glue.

i also redesigned the part that glides on the starting rod. the original wouldn't slice properly, as the walls were too thin. anyway i wanted to have it 4mm inner diameter, so now you have an all new 4mm tube attached, which slides nicely :-)

when i simulated the rocket i found, that with the c6-5 it might be unstable (the c6-5 is a bit heavier than the b's). so i needed to introduce a weight in the top of the cone. to do so, i rebuildt the hollow part of the cone (nasen-innenteil.stl), with which i buildt a negative form out of gypsum to produce a weight made of lead, which exactly fits inside the cone to have it at the topmost point. mine weighed 4.6gr plus a lego 3gr storm-trooper in the cone (didn't want it to fly completely unmanned ;-). both together make the rocked perfectly stable.

the other parts you can directly take from the original. i didn't modify them at all.

oh, and as already mentioned: instead of the recommended streamer i used a 30cm parachute which worked perfectly.

i wasn't able to measure the flight altitude directly, but from some geometrical measurements i saw, that there was a good correlation with the simulation, which makes me believe, that the rocket reached about 365m as simulated. and before you ask - yes i made sure beforehand, that i was allowed to start under this preconditions ;-)

When the controller is mounted, access to the supply and motor wires are quite cumbersome, since the screws are facing downwards. Therefore I also created a stencil for a drill guide. To use it, first place the stencil (and check you have orientated it correct) and trace all the holes with a 2mm drill bit. Then remove the stencil and extend the four corner holes to 4mm, then extend the next six holes to 10mm and finally the last two holes to 25mm. Finally smoothen the edges with a file.

description.text:
A recent customer request, a Replica 1989 Batman Utility Belt. This is definitely going to complete any Michael Keaton Batman costumes out there. It was a great success and I am definitely excited with how it turned out.

You'll need to print:
1x Buckle (adapted from: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:642896)
1x Spacer
2 x Belt

You can use the belt portion for whichever side you chose, it is symmetrical around the buckle and the spacer ensures it fits well around the buckle. I know, the belt is not complete (i.e. full circle). However, you'll notice in the STL files that I have added a 5 mm ring slit behind the bullets to accompany a strap to complete the belt. I did this for 2 reasons: (i) it can fit anyone now; and (ii) you wont see the back if you are wearing a cape!

If you plan on wearing this (because, why the heck not), you need to print the belt pieces in a flexible filament. I used flexible PLA as it maintains is structure but is bendable along its top/bottom surface. Great for this type of use.

If you want one for yourself, message us :) we offer affordable 3D printing solutions throughout Canada.

Also, check out our other work at http://r3dprinting.ca

description.text:
Here as promised on twitter https://twitter.com/MAKE_ME_A_ The snes mini cartridge :D
as first shown in the youtube video https://youtu.be/r4cPfag7xQE

2 Nostalgia nerd video featuring the cart

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3AOmMxdNxlU
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3GRszBZPwAo&feature=youtu.be

The super nintendo classic mini is awesome ... But there's something missing. It doesn't quite look right. So lets fix that :D

The week before the snes mini was released I made this snes mini cartridge but until it arrived on Friday 29th september I couldnt get the measurments of the cart exact until I had mine in hand.

I decided to make a detailed 2 part mini snes cart (second half optional just to make it complete) one half sits on the snes mini and when your not using it just clip the 2 halfs together to make a full mini cart, I might use magnets to hold it in place later but for now a bit of blue tack works fine.

With it been just half a cartridge you dont have to open up or damage your lovely snes mini :D

printed on fine settings with 40% infil, 8 layer brim and support to be on the safe side as there are a couple of small holes.

I bought a 10mtr sample of premium light grey filament from 3d filaprint, they supply awesome samples that you can test before you commit to buying a full reel, the 10 mtrs was just enough to make the cartridge as it used just over 8mtrs.

FilaPrint Light Grey Premium PLA 10 mtr sample £2.89 (1/10/17) http://shop.3dfilaprint.com/filaprint...

FilaPrint Light Grey Premium PLA Full reel £20.95 (1/10/17) http://shop.3dfilaprint.com/filaprint... The premium filament printed amazing, as a result im going to be buying a full reel of it.
